{{Infobox person |honorific_prefix = ''' Amma''' |name = Maniammai |image = |birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1917|3|10}}<ref name="Muthiah2008">{{cite book|author=S. Muthiah|title=Madras, Chennai: A 400-year Record of the First City of Modern India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tbR_LLkqdI8C&pg=PA413|year=2008|publisher=Palaniappa Brothers|isbn=978-81-8379-468-8|pages=413}}</ref> |birth_place = [[Vellore]], [[Madras Presidency]], [[British India]] |death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1978|3|16|1917|3|10}}<ref name="Muthiah2008" /> |death_place = |other_names = |spouse = [[Periyar E. V. Ramasamy]] (m. 1949; d. 1973) }}
'''Maniammai''' (10 March 1917 – 16 March 1978) was an activist and rationalist leader from [[Tamil Nadu]]. She was also the adopted daughter and life partner of [[Periyar E. V. Ramasamy]], and succeeded him as the leader of the [[Dravidar Kazhagam]] upon his death in 1973. She is considered the first woman political leader from the state.
==Biography== Maniammai was born as Gandhimathi to Kanagasabai Mudaliar who was a party member of the [[Justice Party (India)|Justice Party]].<ref name=TT>{{cite news|url=http://www.tamiltribune.com/05/1201.html|title=Periyar Drops a Bombshell|last=Nalankilli|first=Thanjai|newspaper=Tamil tribune|accessdate=19 August 2016}}</ref> Soon after her father's death, she was adopted by [[Periyar E. V. Ramasamy]] and joined the [[Dravidar Kazhagam]] founded by in 1942–43. Periyar's marriage with a much younger Maniammai and his appointment of her as his successor shocked many of his party leaders.<ref name="Bhosale2004">{{cite book|author=Balkrishna Vithal Bhosale|title=Mobilisation of Backward Communities in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9FmeipZ5UnkC&pg=PA222|year=2004|publisher=Deep & Deep|isbn=978-81-7629-588-8|page=222}}</ref> Periyar's disciple [[C. N. Annadurai]] stated that Periyar had set a bad example by marrying a much younger woman. He formed a new party called [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]].<ref name="Zuckerman2009">{{cite book|author=Phil Zuckerman|title=Atheism and Secularity &#91;2 volumes&#93;|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z1hbaAHsAlUC&pg=RA1-PA143|year=2009|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-35182-2|page=143}}</ref>
